    <stitle>ELECTRICAL SYSTEM TROUBLESHOOTING GUIDE - 9800 - VISCOUS FAN DRIVES - TROUBLESHOOTING - VISCOUS FAN DRIVE
        TEST PROCEDURE (BI-METAL DRIVES ONLY)
    </stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcproc id="x1200208" svcproctype="troubleshoot" graphiccount="5">
        <title>VISCOUS FAN DRIVE TEST PROCEDURE (BI-METAL DRIVES ONLY)</title>
        <svcprocinfo>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>This test is most effective at an ambient air temperature of 80&#176;F (26.7&#176;C) or
                        higher.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
        </svcprocinfo>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Diagnostic Procedure</title>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Perform all of the steps in
                    <hotlnk document="s12002y_3.xml" xrefid="x1200201">MAINTENANCE CHECK</hotlnk>
                    <xref refid="x1200201"/>.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Check for obstructions in the radiator, charge air cooler, air conditioning condenser,
                    and transmission cooler (if equipped). Remove any dirt, bugs, lint, or debris in the air path
                    through the radiator to the engine. Pressure wash if necessary.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>To prevent damage, do not direct high-pressure spray onto the fan drive bi-metal. Also, the
                        high-pressure wash must be directed squarely at the front, or rear, of the radiator to prevent
                        radiator fin damage.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Ensure the cooling system is properly filled with the correct coolant mixtures (not to
                    exceed 60% ethylene glycol).
                </para>
            </step1>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>In the following step, warming up a cold engine prior to test preparation will shorten the
                        run-time during the test procedure.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">If engine is cold, start engine and:</para>
            </step1>
            <randlist type="bullet">
                <item>
                    <para>turn air conditioning OFF,</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>turn heater OFF (NOTE: on buses, turn heater supply valves OFF at the engine),</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>run until thermostat opens; then,
                        <emph type="bold">turn engine OFF</emph>.
                    </para>
                </item>
            </randlist>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>In the following step, nylon fan blades (yellow in color) may require painting with flat black
                        paint in order to measure fan speed.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Apply a strip of reflective tape to one (1) blade of the fan and another strip to the
                    fan drive shaft so that fan RPM and fan drive shaft RPM can be measured with the digital
                    photo-tachometer (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f1200206">Figure 3</hotlnk>).
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f1200206" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg12/g1200206.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="448px"
                         scalefitheight="312px" resolution="100"/>
                <caption>Figure 3. Placement of Reflective Tape</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1>1. REFLECTIVE TAPE ON FAN BLADE</callout1>
                    <callout1>2. REFLECTIVE TAPE ON FAN DRIVE SHAFT</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Connect EZ-Tech service tool. If testing a non-electronic engine, measure coolant
                    temperature with a suitable thermometer.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Fabricate a cardboard cover that covers the entire frontal area of the radiator. Cut a 5
                    inch (12.7 cm) hole in the area that aligns with the fan drive bi-metal. Position the cardboard in
                    front of the radiator and tape as necessary to hold in place.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Carefully position the temperature probe so that it measures air temperature within 1
                    inch (2.54 cm) of the fan drive bi-metal. You can safely insert the probe through the A/C condenser,
                    CAC, and radiator core (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f1200207">Figure 4</hotlnk>
                    and
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f1200208">Figure 5</hotlnk>) .
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f1200207" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg12/g1200207.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="448px"
                         scalefitheight="248px" resolution="100"/>
                <caption>Figure 4. Temperature Probe Inserted through Cardboard and Front of Radiator</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1>1. TEMPERATURE PROBE</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
            <figure id="f1200208" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg12/g1200208.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="448px"
                         scalefitheight="272px" resolution="100"/>
                <caption>Figure 5. Positioning of Temperature Probe</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1>1. Temperature probe must be positioned in this area [(1 inch (2.54 cm) from bi-metal)].
                    </callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Start the engine and:</para>
            </step1>
            <randlist type="bullet">
                <item>
                    <para>turn the air conditioning OFF,</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>turn electrical loads ON (lights, etc.),</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>turn heater OFF (on buses, turn heater supply valves OFF).</para>
                </item>
            </randlist>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>In the following step the fan drive shaft speed is not the same as engine speed.</para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Raise the engine speed until the
                    <emph type="underscr">fan drive shaft</emph>
                    reaches 2500 RPM (measured with digital photo-tach).
                    <emph type="underscr">Do not measure fan speed yet.</emph>
                </para>
            </step1>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>Bright sunlight may make it difficult to take RPM measurements using the photo-tachometer.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Lock the throttle at this RPM (use PTO/cruise switches if available). This establishes
                    the fan drive shaft
                    <emph type="boldundersc">TEST</emph>
                    RPM.
                </para>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>If engine cannot achieve 2500 RPM fan drive shaft input speed, test at the highest
                            obtainable RPM.
                        </para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Measure fan blade speed with the digital photo-tachometer (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f1200209">Figure 6</hotlnk>).
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f1200209" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg12/g1200209.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="448px"
                         scalefitheight="432px" resolution="100"/>
                <caption>Figure 6. Measuring Fan Blade Speed with Digital Photo-Tachometer</caption>
            </figure>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>If the vehicle is equipped with shutters, they should open automatically before the fan drive
                        engages.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <step1 id="x1200211">
                <para count="1">As the engine is warming up:</para>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">The fan RPM should stabilize between 800 and 1000 RPM. Some DD-30 and DD-34 fan
                        drives may stabilize at up to 1300 RPM. Refer to
                        <hotlnk xrefid="t1200204">Table 3</hotlnk>
                        for fan drive information
                        <xref refid="t1200204"/>
                        .
                    </para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">As engine coolant temperature reaches 200-220&#176;F (93.3-104.4&#176;C), (refer to
                        <hotlnk xrefid="f1200210">Figure 7</hotlnk>), fan speed should increase to 2125 RPM or higher
                        (85% of the test RPM).
                    </para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">The air temperature at the bi-metal should be between 165&#176;F (73.9&#176;C) and
                        195&#176;F (90.6&#176;C) when the fan engages (
                        <hotlnk xrefid="f1200210">Figure 7</hotlnk>). Refer to
                        <hotlnk xrefid="t1200204">Table 3</hotlnk>
                        for specific fan drive P/N calibration information
                        <xref refid="t1200204"/>.
                    </para>
                </step2>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f1200210" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg12/g1200210.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="448px"
                         scalefitheight="432px" resolution="100"/>
                <caption>Figure 7. Measuring the Coolant and Air Temperatures</caption>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">With the fan engaged,
                    <emph type="underscr">record fan RPM, coolant temperature, and air temperature at bi-metal.</emph>
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Maintain the
                    <emph type="bold">TEST</emph>
                    RPM, with the fan engaged, by keeping the engine speed constant. As temperatures decrease, fan speed
                    should begin to decrease. After 2-3 minutes the fan should slow to the initial fan speed
                    (approximately 40% of the
                    <emph type="bold">TEST</emph>
                    RPM).
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Allow fan to repeat this cycle several times while recording temperatures and fan RPM.
                </para>
            </step1>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Conclusion:</title>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">If the fan fails to reach 2125 RPM or higher (or 85% of input speed) at 200 - 220&#176;F
                    (93.3-104.4&#176;C) coolant temperature, and the air temperature at the bi-metal exceeds 195&#176;F
                    (90.6&#176;C), replace the viscous fan drive.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">If the fan fails to reach 2125 RPM or higher (or 85% of input speed), and the coolant
                    temperature exceeds 220&#176;F (104.4&#176;C), and the air temperature at the bi-metal does not
                    exceed 195&#176;F (90.6&#176;C); then the fan drive is not faulty. Inspect the vehicle for the
                    following:
                </para>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Air flow restrictions (through the CAC and radiator)</para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Internal radiator plugging</para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Faulty thermostat</para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Defective water pump</para>
                </step2>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">When the fan drive disengages (with the 2500
                    <emph type="bold">TEST</emph>
                    RPM maintained), if the fan speed fails to slow to 800-1000 RPM; replace the fan drive (except DD-30
                    and DD-34, see step 13a of the
                    <hotlnk xrefid="x1200208">VISCOUS FAN DRIVE TEST PROCEDURE</hotlnk>
                    <xref refid="x1200208"/>).
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the temperature probe from the radiator.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the cardboard from the front of the radiator.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Return the engine to "idle" and allow the engine to cool for two (2) minutes before
                    shutting down.
                </para>
            </step1>
